Erin Bates (ICC supplied) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories The International Relations Minister has signed notice for SA to leave the ICC.WATCHCAPE TOWN &mdash; Watch this debate on South Africa's decision to withdraw from the International Criminal Court (ICC).ICC head Sidiki Kaba is scheduled to address the South African government's in a briefing in Dakar on Monday, 24 October at 15:00.After news broke last week of South Africa's notice to withdraw Sudan's President Omar al-Bashir called on other African countries to leave the ICC.In a statement from the Sudanese presidency a spokesperson said the ICC targeted African countries but not European states or Israel.South Africa's leading opposition party, the Democratic Alliance, wants the departure decision to be heard by the Constitutional Court of South Africa.Lawson Naidoo from the Council for the Advancement of the South African Constitution (Casac) joined News24's Erin Bates to debate the topic live on Monday.Casac has launched its own application for an urgent hearing on the Minister of International Relations and Cooperation signing a notice of withdrawal.Naidoo said Casac's legal advisers in Johannesburg have asked the Constitutional Court in South Africa to hear their application on an urgent basis.The council hopes it will be heard on the same day as the matter of Omar al-Bashir's exit from South Africa in 2015.According to the rules of the Rome Statute South Africa was obliged to extradite the Sudanese leader to the ICC for hearing.He is, according to the ICC, still at large with 12 other accused of gross human rights violations.&nbsp;"We need to be demonstrating our support from the victims of human rights abuses and not for the perpetrators," said Naidoo."And our decision to withdraw from the Rome Statue gives succor to the perpetrators of genocide."Watch the interview below.24.com encourages commentary submit